<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Molecular affinities.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
The typical quadripartite structure of the newly sequenced plastome has size of 152,355 bp (37.7% GC content) consisting of a large single copy (LSC: 83,371 bp, 35.8% GC content), a small single copy (SSC: 18,562 bp, 31.4% GC content), inverted repeats (IRs: 25,211 bp, 43.1% GC contents each of IRA and IRB) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution of Saussurea talungensis S. K. Ghimire &amp; H. K. Rana A, B distribution map showing type locality in Nepal and Humla district respectively C, D type locality habitat between Nyalu Pass and Ning Tsho, Talung valley, Humla district E quadripartite plastome map of S. talungensis (Photographs C, D and plant picture in E by S. K. Ghimire)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.61996.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531768" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">1E</figureCitation>
). The newly sequenced chloroplast genome was used to determine the phylogenomic relationship of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. talungensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="talungensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. talungensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with its allied species and infer its position within 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Saussurea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saussurea" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Saussurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The molecular phylogeny through BI and ML tree revealed that 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. talungensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="talungensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. talungensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is nested within a clade comprising 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. roylei" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="roylei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. roylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lanata" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="lanata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. lanata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. hookeri" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="hookeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. hookeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. eriostemon" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="eriostemon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. eriostemon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wall. ex C.B.Clarke, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. leontodontoides" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="leontodontoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. leontodontoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(DC.) Sch.Bip., 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. paleacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="paleacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. paleacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Y.L.Chen &amp; S.Y.Liang, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. centiloba" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="centiloba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. centiloba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hand.-Mazz., 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. stella" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="stella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. stella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Maxim. and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. andryaloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="andryaloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. andryaloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(DC.) Sch.Bip. (PP&gt; 0.98, BS&gt; 93%; Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Complete chloroplast genome sequence-based phylogenomic tree inferred from Maximum Likelihood (ML) analyses. Numbers above branches are Bayesian posterior probability (PP) / Likelihood bootstrap support (BS) from BI and ML, respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.61996.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531771" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">4</figureCitation>
). It is more evident that 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. talungensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="talungensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. talungensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a sister to 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. roylei" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="roylei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. roylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(an allied species), and is supported by Bayesian posterior probability (PP = 1) and Likelihood bootstrap support (BS = 98%) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Complete chloroplast genome sequence-based phylogenomic tree inferred from Maximum Likelihood (ML) analyses. Numbers above branches are Bayesian posterior probability (PP) / Likelihood bootstrap support (BS) from BI and ML, respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.61996.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531771" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">4</figureCitation>
). Also, complete chloroplast genome structure is conservative in overall size and the order and size of each gene and intergenic region (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution of Saussurea talungensis S. K. Ghimire &amp; H. K. Rana A, B distribution map showing type locality in Nepal and Humla district respectively C, D type locality habitat between Nyalu Pass and Ning Tsho, Talung valley, Humla district E quadripartite plastome map of S. talungensis (Photographs C, D and plant picture in E by S. K. Ghimire)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.61996.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531768" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">1E</figureCitation>
). The identical BI and ML phylogenomic tree using plastome sequence revealed that 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. talungensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="talungensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. talungensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. roylei" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="roylei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">S. roylei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Complete chloroplast genome sequence-based phylogenomic tree inferred from Maximum Likelihood (ML) analyses. Numbers above branches are Bayesian posterior probability (PP) / Likelihood bootstrap support (BS) from BI and ML, respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.176.61996.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/531771" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">4</figureCitation>
), which is in congruence with the morphological observations.
</paragraph>
